    "summary": "DatoCMS exposes a GraphQL Content Delivery API, an HTTP Content Management API, an MCP server at mcp.datocms.com, and a CLI; API-token auth is required for the two APIs, MCP uses browser OAuth, and CLI auth is OAuth-based but exact command mechanics weren’t pinned down.",
    "credentials": {
      "datocms_api_token": {
        "type": "bearer",
        "label": "DatoCMS API token",
        "generateUrl": "https://www.datocms.com/docs/content-management-api/authentication",
        "setup": "Go to your project administrative area, e.g. `http://your-project.admin.datocms.com`, then open _Project Settings > API Tokens_ and copy or create a token. Every project includes a read-only token by default. For write/delete access, create a custom token with the needed role permissions. Enable the relevant API flags, especially `Access the Content Delivery API` or `Access the Content Delivery API in Preview Mode` for CDA use, and use the token as `Authorization: Bearer <YOUR-API-TOKEN>`."
      },
      "datocms_mcp_oauth": {
        "type": "oauth2",
        "label": "DatoCMS MCP OAuth",
        "generateUrl": "https://mcp.datocms.com",
        "setup": "Add the remote MCP server at `https://mcp.datocms.com` in your MCP client. The server uses native MCP OAuth, so you authorize in the browser during connection; no API token or env vars are needed. For example, in Claude Code run `claude mcp add --transport http DatoCMS https://mcp.datocms.com`, then complete the browser OAuth flow."
      },
      "datocms_cli_oauth": {
        "type": "oauth2",
        "label": "DatoCMS CLI OAuth",
        "generateUrl": "https://www.datocms.com/docs/cli",
        "setup": "Use the DatoCMS CLI login flow when you need a project link or other CLI-authenticated actions. The product update says the CLI now uses OAuth for safer project linking, so the easiest path is to run the CLI command that initiates login/auth in your terminal (the exact login subcommand is not surfaced in the pages I read)."
      }
    },
